It was very very good. I loved everything except the booking part which took me a while.

Too fast, too loud, too hot. We've been going regularly to Gary Danko ourselves since the early 2000's and have taken guests there many times. The food, wines, etc. are still good, but last night it seemed that Gary was no longer minding the store. Unfortunately, most reviewers and many patrons, particularly tourists, believe that all that matters in a restaurant is the food. As usual, last night we ordered wine pairing with our dinner and expected it would be a slow-paced elegant experience as it has always been. Negative. First "too": They threw the food at us. To start, we ordered cocktails first and were pressured several times to order our dinner courses. This became a battle requiring us to ward off the assaults about ordering. Before our drinks were finished we succumbed to the pressure and ordered. Insisting that we order all the courses at the beginning, I was sure to tell the waiter we don't want rapid fire feeding, but good service. It didn't happen. Almost as soon as our order was taken, the sommelier served our wine for the first course (with our cocktails sitting on the table) and almost immediately following that, our first course was served. We barely finished the first course when the sommelier again came to the table while our cocktails and the wine from the first course were still on the table. It looked like a glassware display! Again, our second course came whizzing out of the kitchen. We began eating and I told my wife I was starting to feel sick. Without realizing it because we were there to enjoy ourselves and not looking to criticize, I got a nervous stomach. I then told our waiter and two others on the service team to hold our next course for at least ten minutes. Guess what? Right away, another server came flying out with course three. We sent it back. A manager came to the table, we explained, he apologized. He said for the rest of the dinner they will not prepare or serve until we request it. Finally, after some deep breathing and a welcome break, we resumed the balance of our dinner in normal fashion. My wife and I calculated that based on the initial pace (or race) of the dinner, we would have been finished in 45 minutes. This for a restaurant where usually we dine for 2 1/2 to 3 hours. Second "too": Too noisy and loud. This was not evident in past years, but now the place seems more crowded and the demographics seem to be a lower element given to raucous behavior. The place is beautiful in terms of visual aesthetics, but auditory aesthetics are poor. They need some acoustical treatment, particularly to the ceiling. This is relatively cheap and would not mar the beauty of the interior. Third "too": Too hot. Yes, it was an uncharacteristically warm day in San Francisco, but a restaurant of this stature must have a functioning air conditioning system. There is more, but one other fact has to be addressed: the dress code. This is a fiction. Pigs and slobs have invaded this establishment and it seems to be accepted. If you want to "pig out" either take out the food or go to a sty. This was an elegant restaurant and it is losing its elegance because of the patrons. We saw it start slipping about ten years ago when every man was wearing a coat and tie with the exception of a guy who brought his wife and three children all looking like they came directly from hiking. Last night, my wife and I saw a man walking across the room and we thought he must have been there to repair the AC. Wrong, he was a customer. He was wearing a pair of drooping old work jeans and a tee shirt. About one-third of the men were wearing jackets (two with ties) and the rest were dressed as if they were eating popcorn and watching a basketball game in their living room. The women were generally nicely dressed. Is this Gary Danko's fault? YES! If you wimp out so that you don't miss every last buck you can grab, anything goes and who knows what the future will bring. This dress code must be enforced and all making reservations should be so informed - no jeans, no collarless shirts, etc. and all men must wear a jacket. If they show up without one, they should be given one to wear or denied entry. It's a small restaurant. They won't need to keep many jackets. My wife and I are heartbroken because this has been our "go-to" place for years, but I think they've lost us. (Forgive any errors because I have tears in my eyes, so to speak)

Probably one of the one of the best restaurants in San Francisco. Gary Danko is always packed during good and bad times in the economy. I highly recommend going with the 4 course menu. Start with the Branzini which is an amazing light fish. Then hit up the lobster dish which is amazing. Next hit up either the beef or pork dish. You definitely need a nice red wine to enjoy with that. Finally, finish off with the classic cheese cart. The best cheeses to enjoy solo or with your date, and you get roughly 5 or so to choose from. If you aren't a cheese fan, then for dessert hit up the banana flam prepared table side. The service at GD is impeccable and very top-notch. The corkage fee is a bit steep at $50, which it should be no more than $35. I highly recommend dressing up, so you don't feel out of place. It's always best to overdress than to underdress. They have valet parking as well which is a plus. Overall, Gary Danko is a wonderful experience and I will be coming back here over and over again.

    Too fast, too loud, too hot.

    We've been going regularly to Gary Danko ourselves since the early 2000's and have taken guests there many times. The food, wines, etc. are still good, but last night it seemed that Gary was no longer minding the store. Unfortunately, most reviewers and many patrons, particularly tourists, believe that all that matters in a restaurant is the food. As usual, last night we ordered wine pairing with our dinner and expected it would be a slow-paced elegant experience as it has always been. Negative.

    First "too": They threw the food at us. To start, we ordered cocktails first and were pressured several times to order our dinner courses. This became a battle requiring us to ward off the assaults about ordering. Before our drinks were finished we succumbed to the pressure and ordered. Insisting that we order all the courses at the beginning, I was sure to tell the waiter we don't want rapid fire feeding, but good service. It didn't happen. Almost as soon as our order was taken, the sommelier served our wine for the first course (with our cocktails sitting on the table) and almost immediately following that, our first course was served. We barely finished the first course when the sommelier again came to the table while our cocktails and the wine from the first course were still on the table. It looked like a glassware display!

    Again, our second course came whizzing out of the kitchen. We began eating and I told my wife I was starting to feel sick. Without realizing it because we were there to enjoy ourselves and not looking to criticize, I got a nervous stomach. I then told our waiter and two others on the service team to hold our next course for at least ten minutes. Guess what? Right away, another server came flying out with course three. We sent it back. A manager came to the table, we explained, he apologized. He said for the rest of the dinner they will not prepare or serve until we request it. Finally, after some deep breathing and a welcome break, we resumed the balance of our dinner in normal fashion. My wife and I calculated that based on the initial pace (or race) of the dinner, we would have been finished in 45 minutes. This for a restaurant where usually we dine for 2 1/2 to 3 hours.

    Second "too": Too noisy and loud. This was not evident in past years, but now the place seems more crowded and the demographics seem to be a lower element given to raucous behavior. The place is beautiful in terms of visual aesthetics, but auditory aesthetics are poor. They need some acoustical treatment, particularly to the ceiling. This is relatively cheap and would not mar the beauty of the interior.

    Third "too": Too hot. Yes, it was an uncharacteristically warm day in San Francisco, but a restaurant of this stature must have a functioning air conditioning system.

    There is more, but one other fact has to be addressed: the dress code. This is a fiction. Pigs and slobs have invaded this establishment and it seems to be accepted. If you want to "pig out" either take out the food or go to a sty. This was an elegant restaurant and it is losing its elegance because of the patrons. He was wearing a pair of drooping old work jeans and a tee shirt. About one-third of the men were wearing jackets (two with ties) and the rest were dressed as if they were eating popcorn and watching a basketball game in their living room. The women were generally nicely dressed.

    Is this Gary Danko's fault? YES!  If you wimp out so that you don't miss every last buck you can grab, anything goes and who knows what the future will bring.

    This dress code must be enforced and all making reservations should be so informed - no jeans, no collarless shirts, etc. and all men must wear a jacket. If they show up without one, they should be given one to wear or denied entry. It's a small restaurant. They won't need to keep many jackets.

    My wife and I are heartbroken because this has been our "go-to" place for years, but I think they've lost us. (Forgive any errors because I have tears in my eyes, so to speak)

You can even double pick the same thing if you like it that much! (Which is what my mother in law did. She loved their foie gras so much she ordered it twice). And at the end of the meal, besides the dessert you picked, they also give you a complimentary platter of mini French pastries, and yes, like all the other reviews have mentioned, they even give you a mini cake to take home as a gift for breakfast the next day. A lot of people have mentioned pineapple cake, but I think it varies each season. We got a pumpkin cream cheese cake this time!

    Just a tip, highly recommend everyone to study and research the menu, and also what everyone else has reviewed for certain dishes. Cause the menu can be a bit overwhelming and you want to make sure you know what's good and what you want upon arriving! Bon appetit!

    I took my boyfriend here for his birthday earlier in the month. I made reservations about a month before to ensure we would have a place to celebrate. I read countless reviews, asked numerous questions and found out everything I needed before taking him there. I knew Gary Danko was the place to go. The day came and I choose to park at a nearby garage (I made other plans for the rest of the night) so we did not use the valet. Upon entering we were welcomed with polite and friendly hellos and smiles. Once my name was located on the reservation list we were lead to our table. The usher helped me into my chair, checked my coat and instantly asked us if we wanted sparkling or still water. He immediately got our water and let us review the menu and wine binder. A few moments went by and we had a few questions about the menu. Our waiter answered all our questions and took our order with a smile on his face. He made us extremely happy with our choices, as well as our wine choices. We were able to sit back, relax and enjoy each others company. We were brought bread and butter while we waited for our courses to arrive. When our courses did arrive we were amazed. The portion size was perfect, the presentation was gorgeous and the flavor was outstanding. All courses were absolutely wonderful. Our waiter even brought out a lemon tart for my boyfriends birthday, on the house.

    Now the real critic was my boyfriend, it was his birthday celebration after all. I'm happy to say that he was extremely happy with his birthday and he even stated that the food was just as good as his late grandmothers.

    All in all, I would 100% recommended, and I will definitely return.
